Hornworts
The defining characteristic of the hornworts Anthocerotophyta is the narrow pipelike sporophyte Hornworts
have colonized a variety of habitats on land although they are never far from a source of moisture The short
bluegreen gametophyte is the dominant phase of the life cycle of a hornwort The sporophytes emerge from the
parent gametophyte and continue to grow throughout the life of the plant Figure 2512
Figure 2512 Hornwort sporophytes Hornworts grow a tall and slender sporophyte credit modification of work by
Jason Hollinger
Stomata air pores that can be opened and closed appear in the hornworts and are abundant on the sporophyte
Photosynthetic cells in the thallus each contain a single chloroplast Meristem cells at the base of the plant
